Good. This is the last foundational engine layer.

After this, your system is no longer “a framework in pieces” — it becomes a **fully deterministic navigation engine for interactive worlds**.

---

# 🧠 TRANSITION ENGINE V2 (OFFICIAL DESIGN)

This system controls:

> how the player moves from one node to another — and *why*

It is the bridge between:

* node definitions
* player decisions
* timers
* effects
* failure states
* runtime history

---

# 🚨 CORE PRINCIPLE

## ❌ Nodes do NOT decide navigation directly

## ❌ Effects do NOT move the player

## ❌ UI does NOT control flow

## ✅ The Transition Engine is the ONLY authority on movement

Everything else *requests*, it decides.

---

# 🧱 TRANSITION ENGINE HAS 4 STAGES

```txt id="tr0"
INPUT → EVALUATE → RESOLVE → EXECUTE
```

---

# 🥇 1. TRANSITION INPUT

Triggered by:

* player choice click
* node auto-next
* timer expiration
* fail condition
* effect-triggered jump (rare, controlled)

Example input:

```json id="tr1"
{
  "type": "choice",
  "fromNodeId": "puzzle_001",
  "choiceId": "choice_echo"
}
```

or:

```json id="tr2"
{
  "type": "timer_expired",
  "nodeId": "puzzle_001"
}
```

---

# 🥈 2. EVALUATION LAYER (GUARD CHECKS)

This is where decisions are validated.

## Checks:

### ✔ Node exists

### ✔ Choice exists (if applicable)

### ✔ Requirements satisfied

### ✔ Flags valid

### ✔ Inventory conditions met

### ✔ Fail conditions checked first

---

## 🧠 ORDER OF EVALUATION

This order is critical:

```txt id="tr3"
1. Fail conditions
2. Requirements
3. Choice validity
4. Default transitions
```

---

## Example FAIL OVERRIDE:

If node has:

```json id="tr4"
"failNodeId": "trap_001"
```

AND conditions fail → override all transitions.

---

# 🥉 3. TRANSITION RESOLUTION

Now we determine:

> WHERE DO WE GO?

We resolve in this priority order:

---

## 🧭 PRIORITY ORDER

### 1. Choice-based transition

```json id="tr5"
choice.next
```

---

### 2. Node.next (linear flow)

```json id="tr6"
"next": "portal_001"
```

---

### 3. Fail node

```json id="tr7"
"failNodeId": "deadEnd_001"
```

---

### 4. Timer expiration node

```json id="tr8"
timer.onExpireNodeId
```

---

### 5. System fallback

* stay on node
* or go to safe fallback node

---

# 🏁 4. TRANSITION EXECUTION

Once resolved:

```txt id="tr9"
Exit current node
→ run onExit effects
→ apply state updates
→ switch active node
→ run onEnter effects
→ record history
→ render
```

---

# 🧱 OFFICIAL TRANSITION OBJECT

We formalize transitions as first-class objects:

```json id="tr10"
{
  "from": "puzzle_001",
  "to": "end_001",
  "reason": "choice",
  "trigger": "choice_echo",
  "timestamp": 123456
}
```

---

# 🧠 TRANSITION TYPES (CANONICAL SET)

## 1. Choice Transition

Player selects option

```txt id="tr11"
choice_click
```

---

## 2. Linear Transition

Automatic flow

```txt id="tr12"
auto_next
```

---

## 3. Timer Transition

Time-based navigation

```txt id="tr13"
timer_expired
```

---

## 4. Fail Transition

Requirements failed

```txt id="tr14"
fail_condition
```

---

## 5. Effect Transition (controlled)

Special scripted jumps

```txt id="tr15"
effect_triggered_jump
```

⚠️ Must be explicitly allowed in schema rules.

---

# 🧱 TRANSITION GUARD SYSTEM (VERY IMPORTANT)

Before ANY transition executes:

## Guards run:

### ✔ CanLeaveNode(node)

* prevents illegal exits

### ✔ CanEnterNode(node)

* checks requirements again (double safety)

### ✔ CanTransition(from → to)

* ensures graph validity

---

# 🧠 WHY DOUBLE VALIDATION MATTERS

Because creators will build:

* loops
* traps
* conditional puzzles
* broken paths intentionally or accidentally

So the engine must be:

> forgiving at input, strict at execution

---

# 🧱 TRANSITION + EFFECT INTEGRATION

This is the key system interaction:

## EXIT PHASE

```txt id="tr16"
run onExit effects
```

## SWITCH PHASE

```txt id="tr17"
change active node
```

## ENTER PHASE

```txt id="tr18"
run onEnter effects
```

---

# 🧠 CRITICAL DESIGN RULE

## Effects NEVER decide transitions

Instead:

* effects can SET FLAGS
* transitions READ FLAGS

Example:

```txt id="tr19"
Effect → setFlag("door_open")
Transition → checks flag → allows movement
```

This prevents chaos.

---

# 🧱 TRANSITION HISTORY (REQUIRED)

We now log every move:

```json id="tr20"
{
  "from": "start_001",
  "to": "puzzle_001",
  "reason": "auto_next",
  "context": {
    "choiceId": null,
    "flagState": {},
    "inventoryState": {}
  }
}
```

This enables:

* replay system
* debugging tools
* analytics
* creator simulation mode

